<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 2 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ministry of Health, France Press Release [trans. by Mod.MPP]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/display/?doc=presse/2002/communiques/chamonix/index.html>

Q fever epidemic in the Chamonix Valley
---------------------------------------
An epidemic of Q fever has arisen in the Chamonix Valley. [By 30 Aug 2002],
there were 79 [clinical] cases of Q fever in residents of or visitors to
the Chamonix Valley. 22 cases have been confirmed, most of whom live in the
village of Chamonix.
Q fever is an infectious disease caused by _Coxiella burnetii_; a bacterium
that generally infects ruminants (cattle, sheep, and goats). Humans are
usually infected via inhalation of dust or aerosols containing the
responsible organism. The investigations conducted by sanitary authorities
in collaboration with health professionals of the Valley [Chamonix]
coordinating with the agricultural services have not identified the source
of this epidemic as yet. Q fever is not transmitted from person to person.
In the majority of cases, the infection is sub-clinical. When illness
presents it is after an incubation period of an average of 2 weeks, and
presents as a flu-like syndrome associated with a high fever, chills,
headaches, nausea, and aches. The illness usually resolves after 7 to 10
days, often without specific treatment.
In people with valvular heart disease or other serious disease associated
with impaired immunity Q fever can evolve into a chronic disorder. Such
people, when infected, require medical follow-up and prolonged antibiotic
treatment. Infection can lead to spontaneous abortion in pwomen in the
early months of pregnancy.
People who live in or have visited the Chamonix Valley since June 2002 may
have been exposed to the risk of infection. People who belong to identified
risk groups (valvular heart disease, immunocompromise, pregnant) are
recommended to consult their physicians for testing to identify if
antibiotic therapy is indicated.
Additional information can be found on the following websites (in French):
Ministère de la Santé ( www.sante.gouv.fr ), l'Institut de Veille Sanitaire
( www.invs.sante.fr ), and the Centre National de Référence (
http://ifr48.free.fr ).
--
